<p></p>
<p><br></p>
<p>Detailed documentation is here: <a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpa=
c.com.au/x/7StQW" rel=3D"nofollow">Rate Limiting in Mesh Gateways (Axway an=
d Kong)</a></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>What is TPS&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(34,34,34);">TPS (Transaction per Second)&nbsp;=
</span><span style=3D"color: rgb(34,34,34);">is the overall limit of calls =
your back end can process per second. Both the Kong gateway (for APIs) and =
the Axway gateway (for proxies) treat TPS as transactions =E2=80=98processe=
d=E2=80=99 per second (request &amp; response).</span></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong><span style=3D"color: rgb(34,34,34);">Frequently Asked Questions=
&nbsp;</span></strong></p>
<h4 id=3D"TPSFrequentlyAskedQuestions-IfanAPIissetto1TPS,doesitmeanthatonly=
onerequestcanbereceivedbyAPIeverysecond?Alladditionalrequestswillbeterminat=
edbythegateway?">If an API is set to 1 TPS, does it mean that only one requ=
est can be received by API every second? All additional requests will be te=
rminated by the gateway ?</h4>
<p>Ans&nbsp; - the rate limit or quota is on the number of new requests acc=
epted within each one-second window. If you have a TPS limit of say 1 TPS a=
 second call within the same second will be rejected.The consumers&nbsp; wi=
ll get a 429 =E2=80=93 Too many requests.<br><br>
 You should&nbsp;<em>not</em> assume any special behaviour for very long-ru=
nning requests.</p>
<h4 id=3D"TPSFrequentlyAskedQuestions-Doesitconsiderthatthecurrentrequestis=
processedandaresponsereturnedbeforeacceptinganynewrequestORitonlyconsidersr=
equestspersecond?Inotherwordswhatdoes=E2=80=9CTransaction=E2=80=9DinTPSrefe=
rtoaRequestonlyorRequest&amp;ResponsemakesaTransaction.">Does it consider t=
hat the current request is processed and a response returned before accepti=
ng any new request OR it only considers requests per second? In other words=
 what does =E2=80=9CTransaction=E2=80=9D in TPS refer to a Request only or =
Request &amp; Response makes a Transaction.</h4>
<p>Ans:&nbsp; Transaction in TPS refers to Request and Response. ie&nbsp;<s=
pan style=3D"color: rgb(34,34,34);">transactions =E2=80=98processed=E2=80=
=99 per second.&nbsp;</span></p>
<h4 id=3D"TPSFrequentlyAskedQuestions-IsTimeoutsettinglinkedtoTPSoritscompl=
etelyindependent?">Is Timeout setting linked to TPS or its completely indep=
endent?</h4>
<p>Ans: No it is not linked to TPS</p>
<h4 id=3D"TPSFrequentlyAskedQuestions-WhereisTPSenforcedforapplicationscall=
ingAPIs?IsTPSenforcedper-consumerorfortheservice?">Where is TPS enforced fo=
r applications calling APIs? Is TPS enforced per-consumer or for the servic=
e?</h4>
<p>Ans: For application to API calls, TPS is enforced in <strong>Kong</stro=
ng> and a limit is applied for the&nbsp;<strong>service</strong>. The limit=
 is calculated as the sum of individual consumer limits by default, and can=
 be set explicitly using <code>resources.yaml</code>.&nbsp;</p>
<h4 id=3D"TPSFrequentlyAskedQuestions-WhereisTPSenforcedforapplicationscall=
ingserviceproxies?IsTPSenforcedper-consumerorfortheservice?">Where is TPS e=
nforced for applications calling service proxies? Is TPS enforced per-consu=
mer or for the service?</h4>
<p>Ans: For application to service proxy calls, TPS is enforced in <strong>=
Axway</strong> and a limit is applied for each consuming <strong>applicatio=
n</strong>. This is the limit allowed by the consumption grants process.</p=
>
<h4 id=3D"TPSFrequentlyAskedQuestions-IsTPSenforcedforAPIscallingAPIsorserv=
iceproxies?">Is TPS enforced for APIs calling APIs or service proxies?</h4>
<p>Ans: No. Currently the servicemesh does not support a suitable rate limi=
ter.</p>
<h4 id=3D"TPSFrequentlyAskedQuestions-WhatisMaxTPS?"><span style=3D"letter-=
spacing: -0.003em;">What is MaxTPS ?</span></h4>
<p>Ans:&nbsp; &nbsp;At the moment, the value in the service-level.yaml is f=
or documentation purpose only. The <strong>enforced </strong>rate limit for=
 Kong is in resources.yaml. For Axway, rate limits are enforced per-consume=
r instead.</p>
<h4 id=3D"TPSFrequentlyAskedQuestions-Iftheconsumerneedstocaterformoreconcu=
rrenttransactionsdotheyrequiretoaskformoreTPS?">If the consumer needs to ca=
ter for more concurrent transactions do they require to ask for more TPS ?&=
nbsp;&nbsp;</h4>
<p>Ans: Yes. Always. For Axway this may directly impact the consumer. For K=
ong, this contributes to the total default rate limit for the service.</p>
<h4 id=3D"TPSFrequentlyAskedQuestions-IfanAPIissetto1TPS,theconsumerwilleff=
ectivelyget4TPSbecauseofthe4APIcontainersrunninginthebackground.Isthiscorre=
ct?">If an API is set to 1 TPS, the consumer will effectively get 4 TPS bec=
ause of the 4 API containers running in the background. Is this correct ?&n=
bsp;</h4>
<p>Ans: No. TPS is not defined at container level instead it is more define=
s at the gateway level. This is true for both Kong and Axway.</p>
<h4 id=3D"TPSFrequentlyAskedQuestions-IftheTPSissetto5TPSthenisitnecessaryt=
hatyouwillgetonly5TPSinproductionandSVP?">If the TPS is set to 5 TPS then i=
s it necessary that you will get only 5 TPS in production and SVP?</h4>
<p>Ans: No. In Kong and in Axway, we are not using shared rate limits. Each=
 gateway instance is maintaining a local rate limit instead. It is always r=
ecommended to not rely on those TPS setting for any strict enforcing at gat=
eway.</p>
<h4 id=3D"TPSFrequentlyAskedQuestions-IstheTPSlimitappliestotheentireAPIorf=
oreachEnd-point?">Is the TPS limit applies to the entire API or for each En=
d-point ?</h4>
<p>Ans: The TPS applies to all the endpoints in the API.&nbsp;</p>
<h4 id=3D"TPSFrequentlyAskedQuestions-IftheTPSlimitreachedandIreceiveda429e=
rror,doIhavetowaitforcertainperiod?OraslongastheTPSdropsbelowthelimit,theca=
llswillsuccess?">If the TPS limit reached and I received a 429 error, do I =
have to wait for certain period? Or as long as the TPS drops below the limi=
t, the calls will success?</h4>
<p>Ans:&nbsp; You will get 429 only when the consumer exceeded the limit. T=
he calls will be successful automatically if the consumer drops the number =
of calls. Rate limit counters reset every second. You only need to consider=
 a backoff delay in specific cases such as processing events from Kafka top=
ics or queues.</p>
<h4 id=3D"TPSFrequentlyAskedQuestions-Wantedtoknowdoweuselocal_cacheordistr=
ibuted_cacheforratelimitonAPIGateway?andwhatisconfiguredinProduction..">Wan=
ted to know do we use local_cache or distributed_cache&nbsp;&nbsp;for rate =
limit on API Gateway ? and what is configured in Production..</h4>
<p>Ans:&nbsp;We aren't actually using a cache for rate limiting.</p>
<p>We are focusing on local rate limiting (per gateway) as basic overload p=
rotection only. In practice the actual maximum throughput will vary based o=
n many factors including how evenly load is spread by consuming application=
s.</p>
<h4 id=3D"TPSFrequentlyAskedQuestions-HowdoestheTPSlimitworksonanAPI?Doesit=
considertheactivethreadsfromprevioussecond?">How does the TPS limit works o=
n an API? Does it consider the active threads from previous second?</h4>
<p>In Kong, rate limits reset every second, and so active requests from a p=
revious second are not considered.</p>
<p>In Axway, it appears based on our testing that counters also reset, alth=
ough the product documentation appears to say otherwise.</p>
<p><strong>Reference</strong></p>
<p><a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/x/7StQW" rel=3D"nofollo=
w">Rate Limiting in Mesh Gateways (Axway and Kong)</a></p>
<p><br></p>
